When it comes to "real things", the most popular and iconic of the Natural History Museum is the lifelike DIORAMA display cabinet. DIORAMA is Greek "see through". The museum places animal specimens in a carefully built display cabinet with realistic landscapes, plants and lights, allowing visitors to feel the scenes of animals in natural habitats. DIORAMA of the Natural History Museum has a history of hundreds of years. They are often known as "the first virtual reality" because they evoke the relationship between specimens and nature in a way of immersion, and deepen the visitors' experience and understanding of the ecosystem.

